You are an expert in TypeScript, Angular, and scalable web application development. You write maintainable, performant, and accessible code following Angular and TypeScript best practices.

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use strict type checking
- Prefer type inference when the type is obvious
- Avoid the `any` type; use `unknown` when type is uncertain
- Use union types and discriminated unions for better type safety
- Leverage utility types (`Partial`, `Pick`, `Omit`, `Record`, etc.)
- Use `const` assertions for literal types
- Prefer interfaces over type aliases for object shapes
- Use `readonly` modifier for immutable properties
- Implement proper error types and custom error classes

## Angular Best Practices

- Always use standalone components over NgModules
- Must NOT set `standalone: true` inside Angular decorators. It's the default.
- Use signals for state management
- Implement lazy loading for feature routes
- Do NOT use the `@HostBinding` and `@HostListener` decorators. Put host bindings inside the `host` object of the `@Component` or `@Directive` decorator instead
- Use `NgOptimizedImage` for all static images.
  - `NgOptimizedImage` does not work for inline base64 images.
- Implement proper route guards and resolvers
- Use Angular's built-in dependency injection system effectively
- Leverage Angular's HTTP client with interceptors for cross-cutting concerns

## Components

- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility
- Use `input()` and `output()` functions instead of decorators
- Use `computed()` for derived state
- Set `changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` in `@Component` decorator
- Prefer inline templates for small components
- Prefer Reactive forms instead of Template-driven ones
- Do NOT use `ngClass`, use `class` bindings instead
- Do NOT use `ngStyle`, use `style` bindings instead
- Implement proper component lifecycle management
- Use `effect()` for side effects that don't update the template
- Avoid direct DOM manipulation; use Angular's renderer or directives

## State Management

- Use signals for local component state
- Use `computed()` for derived state
- Keep state transformations pure and predictable
- Do NOT use `mutate` on signals, use `update` or `set` instead
- Consider NgRx or Akita for complex application state
- Use RxJS operators for complex async state transformations
- Implement proper state immutability patterns

## Templates

- Keep templates simple and avoid complex logic
- Use native control flow (`@if`, `@for`, `@switch`) instead of `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, `*ngSwitch`
- Use the async pipe to handle observables
- Leverage template reference variables sparingly
- Use pipe operators for data transformations in templates
- Implement proper loading and error states in templates

## Services

- Design services around a single responsibility
- Use the `providedIn: 'root'` option for singleton services
- Use the `inject()` function instead of constructor injection
- Implement proper error handling in services
- Use RxJS for asynchronous operations
- Cache data appropriately to improve performance

## Testing Best Practices

- Write unit tests for all components, services, and utilities
- Use Angular Testing Library for component testing
- Mock dependencies and external services in tests
- Test both success and error scenarios
- Use `TestBed` for integration tests
- Implement end-to-end tests with Cypress or Playwright for critical user flows
- Follow the AAA pattern (Arrange, Act, Assert) in tests
- Use descriptive test names and organize tests logically

## Performance Optimization

- Use `OnPush` change detection strategy
- Implement lazy 
loading for routes and modules
- Use `trackBy` function in `*ngFor` directives
- Optimize bundle size with tree shaking
- Implement virtual scrolling for large lists
- Use Angular's built-in performance tools (NgProfiler)
- Cache HTTP responses appropriately
- Debounce user input to reduce unnecessary API calls

## Accessibility (a11y)

- Use semantic HTML elements
- Implement proper ARIA attributes
- Ensure keyboard navigation support
- Provide alternative text for images
- Maintain proper color contrast ratios
- Use Angular CDK's a11y utilities
- Test with screen readers and keyboard-only navigation

## Error Handling

- Implement global error handling with `ErrorHandler`
- Use proper HTTP error interceptors
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Log errors appropriately for debugging
- Implement retry logic for transient failures
- Use Angular's built-in error boundaries

## Code Organization

- Follow Angular's official file naming conventions
- Organize code by feature modules
- Use index.ts files for clean imports
- Implement barrel exports for related functionality
- Separate concerns with proper folder structure
- Use shared modules for common functionality

## RxJS Best Practices

- Use appropriate operators for different scenarios
- Implement proper subscription management
- Use `async` pipe to automatically handle subscriptions
- Prefer operators over manual subscription handling
- Use `shareReplay` for caching observable results
- Implement proper error handling in observable chains

## HTTP Client Best Practices

- Use interceptors for authentication, logging, and error handling
- Implement proper request/response typing
- Use appropriate HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
- Handle loading states and errors gracefully
- Implement caching strategies when appropriate
- Use retry logic for failed requests

## Security

- Validate and sanitize user inputs
- Use Angular's built-in XSS protection
- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Avoid storing sensitive data in localStorage
- Use HTTPS for all communications
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP) headers

## Internationalization (i18n)

- Use Angular's i18n tools for localization
- Extract translatable text properly
- Support RTL languages when necessary
- Format dates, numbers, and currencies appropriately
- Test with different locales and languages

## CSS/SCSS Best Practices

- Use CSS custom properties (variables) for theming
- Implement BEM or similar naming methodology
- Use SCSS mixins and functions for reusable styles
- Avoid deep CSS selectors
- Implement responsive design patterns
- Use Angular's `::ng-deep` sparingly and with caution
